ude an empty pair of parentheses to indicate the absence of the left child. This ensures that the one-to-one mapping between the string representation and the original binary tree structure is maintained.\n\nIn summary, empty parentheses pairs should be omitted when a node has only a left child or no children. However, when a node has a right child but no left child, an empty pair of parentheses must precede the representation of the right child to reflect the tree's structure accurately.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0606-construct-string-from-binary-tree/606-cons1-tree.jpg","sequence":1,"sha256":"f6efc7ec8ddae873302b11010e5da0fb55fede0b005f64236e6d0386006405b5","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: root = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: \"1(2(4))(3)\"\nExplanation: Originally, it needs to be \"1(2(4)())(3()())\", but you need to omit all the empty parenthesis pairs. And it will be \"1(2(4))(3)\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0606-construct-string-from-binary-tree/606-cons2-tree.jpg","sequence":4,"sha256":"72028d466694da84708493570f63e8b9f22b67fed1739018119d7934eea0a774","type":"image"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: root = [1,2,3,null,4]\nOutput: \"1(2()(4))(3)\"\nExplanation: Almost the same as the first example, except the () after 2 is necessary to indicate the absence of a left child for 2 and the presence of a right child.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 10⁴]`.\n\n- `-1000 <= Node.val <= 1000`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["String","Tree","Depth-First Search","Binary Tree"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given the `root` node of a binary tree, your task is to create a str