`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"You are given an array of `n` pairs `pairs` where `pairs[i] = [lefti, righti]` and `lefti < righti`.\n\nA pair `p2 = [c, d]` **follows** a pair `p1 = [a, b]` if `b < c`. A **chain** of pairs can be formed in this fashion.\n\nReturn *the length longest chain which can be formed*.\n\nYou do not need to use up all the given intervals. You can select pairs in any order.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: pairs = [[1,2],[2,3],[3,4]]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: The longest chain is [1,2] -> [3,4].\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: pairs = [[1,2],[7,8],[4,5]]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The longest chain is [1,2] -> [4,5] -> [7,8].\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == pairs.length`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 1000`\n\n- `-1000 <= lefti < righti <= 1000`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-length-of-pair-chain/","problemName":"Maximum Length of Pair Chain","problemNumber":646,"problemSlug":"maximum-length-of-pair-chain","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":646,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Two Pointers","String","Dynamic Programming"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given a string `s`, return *the number of **palindromic substrings** in it*.\n\nA string is a **palindrome** when it reads the same backward as forward.\n\nA **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within the string.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: s = \"abc\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: Three palindromic strings: \"a\", \"b\", \"c\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: s = \"aaa\"\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: Six palindromic strings: \"a\", \"a\", \"a\", \"aa\", \"aa\", \"aaa\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 1000`\n\n- `s` consists of lowercase English letters.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Two Pointers","String","Dynamic Programming"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given a string `s`, return *the number of **palindromic substrings** in it*.\n\nA string is a **palindrome** when it reads the same backward as forward.\n\nA **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within the string.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: s = \"abc\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: Three palindromic strings: \"a\", \"b\", \"c\".\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: s = \"aaa\"\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: Six palindromic strings: \"a\", \"a\", \"a\", \"aa\", \"aa\", \"aaa\".\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 1000`\n\n- `s` consists of lowercase English letters.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/palindromic-substrings/","problemName":"Palindromic Substrings","problemNumber":647,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given a string `s`, return *the number of **palindromic substrings** in it*.\n\nA string is a **palindrome** when it reads the same backward as forward.\n\nA **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within the string.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: s = \"abc\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: Three palindromic strings: \"a\", \"b\", \"c\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: s = \"aaa\"\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: Six palindromic strings: \"a\", \"a\", \"a\", \"aa\", \"aa\", \"aaa\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 1000`\n\n- `s` consists of lowercase English letters.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Given a string `s`, return *the number of **palindromic substrings** in it*.\n\nA string is a **palindrome** when it reads the same backward as forward.\n\nA **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within the string.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: s = \"abc\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: Three palindromic strings: \"a\", \"b\", \"c\".\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: s = \"aaa\"\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: Six palindromic strings: \"a\", \"a\", \"a\", \"aa\", \"aa\", \"aaa\".\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 1000`\n\n- `s` consists of lowercase English letters.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/palindromic-substrings/","problemName":"Palindromic Substrings","problemNumber":647,"problemSlug":"palindromic-substrings","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":647,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Hash Table","String","Trie"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"In English, we have a concept called **root**, which can be followed by some other word to form another longer word - let's call this word **derivative**. For example, when the **root** `\"help\"` is followed by the word `\"ful\"`, we can form a derivative `\"helpful\"`.\n\nGiven a `dictionary` consisting of many **roots** and a `sentence` consisting of words separated by spaces, replace all the derivatives in the sentence with the **root** forming it. If a derivative can be replaced by more than one **root**, replace it with the **root** that has **the shortest length**.\n\nReturn *the `sentence`* after the replacement.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: dictionary = [\"cat\",\"bat\",\"rat\"], sentence = \"the cattle was rattled by the battery\"\nOutput: \"the cat was rat by the bat\"","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: dictionary = [\"a\",\"b\",\"c\"], sentence = \"aadsfasf absbs bbab cadsfafs\"\nOutput: \"a a b c\"","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= dictionary.length <= 1000`\n\n- `1 <= dictionary[i].length <= 100`\n\n- `dictionary[i]` consists of only lower-case letters.\n\n- `1 <= sentence.length <= 10⁶`\n\n- `sentence` consists of only lower-case letters and spaces.\n\n- The number of words in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- The length of each word in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- Every two consecutive words in `sentence` will be separated by exactly one space.\n\n- `sentence` does not have leading or trailing spaces.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Hash Table","String","Trie"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"In English, we have a concept called **root**, which can be followed by some other word to form another longer word - let's call this word **derivative**. For example, when the **root** `\"help\"` is followed by the word `\"ful\"`, we can form a derivative `\"helpful\"`.\n\nGiven a `dictionary` consisting of many **roots** and a `sentence` consisting of words separated by spaces, replace all the derivatives in the sentence with the **root** forming it. If a derivative can be replaced by more than one **root**, replace it with the **root** that has **the shortest length**.\n\nReturn *the `sentence`* after the replacement.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: dictionary = [\"cat\",\"bat\",\"rat\"], sentence = \"the cattle was rattled by the battery\"\nOutput: \"the cat was rat by the bat\"\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: dictionary = [\"a\",\"b\",\"c\"], sentence = \"aadsfasf absbs bbab cadsfafs\"\nOutput: \"a a b c\"\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= dictionary.length <= 1000`\n\n- `1 <= dictionary[i].length <= 100`\n\n- `dictionary[i]` consists of only lower-case letters.\n\n- `1 <= sentence.length <= 10⁶`\n\n- `sentence` consists of only lower-case letters and spaces.\n\n- The number of words in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- The length of each word in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- Every two consecutive words in `sentence` will be separated by exactly one space.\n\n- `sentence` does not have leading or trailing spaces.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/replace-words/","problemName":"Replace Words","problemNumber":648,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"In English, we have a concept called **root**, which can be followed by some other word to form another longer word - let's call this word **derivative**. For example, when the **root** `\"help\"` is followed by the word `\"ful\"`, we can form a derivative `\"helpful\"`.\n\nGiven a `dictionary` consisting of many **roots** and a `sentence` consisting of words separated by spaces, replace all the derivatives in the sentence with the **root** forming it. If a derivative can be replaced by more than one **root**, replace it with the **root** that has **the shortest length**.\n\nReturn *the `sentence`* after the replacement.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: dictionary = [\"cat\",\"bat\",\"rat\"], sentence = \"the cattle was rattled by the battery\"\nOutput: \"the cat was rat by the bat\"","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: dictionary = [\"a\",\"b\",\"c\"], sentence = \"aadsfasf absbs bbab cadsfafs\"\nOutput: \"a a b c\"","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= dictionary.length <= 1000`\n\n- `1 <= dictionary[i].length <= 100`\n\n- `dictionary[i]` consists of only lower-case letters.\n\n- `1 <= sentence.length <= 10⁶`\n\n- `sentence` consists of only lower-case letters and spaces.\n\n- The number of words in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- The length of each word in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- Every two consecutive words in `sentence` will be separated by exactly one space.\n\n- `sentence` does not have leading or trailing spaces.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"In English, we have a concept called **root**, which can be followed by some other word to form another longer word - let's call this word **derivative**. For example, when the **root** `\"help\"` is followed by the word `\"ful\"`, we can form a derivative `\"helpful\"`.\n\nGiven a `dictionary` consisting of many **roots** and a `sentence` consisting of words separated by spaces, replace all the derivatives in the sentence with the **root** forming it. If a derivative can be replaced by more than one **root**, replace it with the **root** that has **the shortest length**.\n\nReturn *the `sentence`* after the replacement.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: dictionary = [\"cat\",\"bat\",\"rat\"], sentence = \"the cattle was rattled by the battery\"\nOutput: \"the cat was rat by the bat\"\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: dictionary = [\"a\",\"b\",\"c\"], sentence = \"aadsfasf absbs bbab cadsfafs\"\nOutput: \"a a b c\"\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= dictionary.length <= 1000`\n\n- `1 <= dictionary[i].length <= 100`\n\n- `dictionary[i]` consists of only lower-case letters.\n\n- `1 <= sentence.length <= 10⁶`\n\n- `sentence` consists of only lower-case letters and spaces.\n\n- The number of words in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- The length of each word in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`\n\n- Every two consecutive words in `sentence` will be separated by exactly one space.\n\n- `sentence` does not have leading or trailing spaces.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/replace-words/","problemName":"Replace Words","problemNumber":648,"problemSlug":"replace-words","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":648,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["String","Greedy","Queue"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"In the world of Dota2, there are two parties: the Radiant and the Dire.\n\nThe Dota2 senate consists of senators coming from two parties. Now the Senate wants to decide on a change in the Dota2 game. The voting for this change is a round-based procedure. In each round, each senator can exercise **one** of the two rights:\n\n- **Ban one senator's right:** A senator can make another senator lose all his rights in this and all the following rounds.\n\n- **Announce the victory:** If this senator found the senators who still have rights to vote are all from the same party, he can announce the victory and decide on the change in the game.\n\nGiven a string `senate` representing each senator's party belonging. The character `'R'` and `'D'` represent the Radiant party and the Dire party. Then if there are `n` senators, the size of the given string will be `n`.\n\nThe round-based procedure starts from the first senator to the last senator in the given order. This procedure will last until the end of voting. All the senators who have lost their rights will be skipped during the procedure.\n\nSuppose every senator is smart enough and will play the best strategy for his own party. Predict which party will finally announce the victory and change the Dota2 game. The output should be `\"Radiant\"` or `\"Dire\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: senate = \"RD\"\nOutput: \"Radiant\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd in round 2, the first senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: senate = \"RDD\"\nOutput: \"Dire\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd the third senator comes from Dire and he can ban the first senator's right in round 1. \nAnd in round 2, the third senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == senate.length`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁴`\n\n- `senate[i]` is either `'R'` or `'D'`.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["String","Greedy","Queue"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"In the world of Dota2, there are two parties: the Radiant and the Dire.\n\nThe Dota2 senate consists of senators coming from two parties. Now the Senate wants to decide on a change in the Dota2 game. The voting for this change is a round-based procedure. In each round, each senator can exercise **one** of the two rights:\n\n- **Ban one senator's right:** A senator can make another senator lose all his rights in this and all the following rounds.\n\n- **Announce the victory:** If this senator found the senators who still have rights to vote are all from the same party, he can announce the victory and decide on the change in the game.\n\nGiven a string `senate` representing each senator's party belonging. The character `'R'` and `'D'` represent the Radiant party and the Dire party. Then if there are `n` senators, the size of the given string will be `n`.\n\nThe round-based procedure starts from the first senator to the last senator in the given order. This procedure will last until the end of voting. All the senators who have lost their rights will be skipped during the procedure.\n\nSuppose every senator is smart enough and will play the best strategy for his own party. Predict which party will finally announce the victory and change the Dota2 game. The output should be `\"Radiant\"` or `\"Dire\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: senate = \"RD\"\nOutput: \"Radiant\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd in round 2, the first senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: senate = \"RDD\"\nOutput: \"Dire\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd the third senator comes from Dire and he can ban the first senator's right in round 1. \nAnd in round 2, the third senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == senate.length`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁴`\n\n- `senate[i]` is either `'R'` or `'D'`.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/dota2-senate/","problemName":"Dota2 Senate","problemNumber":649,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"In the world of Dota2, there are two parties: the Radiant and the Dire.\n\nThe Dota2 senate consists of senators coming from two parties. Now the Senate wants to decide on a change in the Dota2 game. The voting for this change is a round-based procedure. In each round, each senator can exercise **one** of the two rights:\n\n- **Ban one senator's right:** A senator can make another senator lose all his rights in this and all the following rounds.\n\n- **Announce the victory:** If this senator found the senators who still have rights to vote are all from the same party, he can announce the victory and decide on the change in the game.\n\nGiven a string `senate` representing each senator's party belonging. The character `'R'` and `'D'` represent the Radiant party and the Dire party. Then if there are `n` senators, the size of the given string will be `n`.\n\nThe round-based procedure starts from the first senator to the last senator in the given order. This procedure will last until the end of voting. All the senators who have lost their rights will be skipped during the procedure.\n\nSuppose every senator is smart enough and will play the best strategy for his own party. Predict which party will finally announce the victory and change the Dota2 game. The output should be `\"Radiant\"` or `\"Dire\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: senate = \"RD\"\nOutput: \"Radiant\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd in round 2, the first senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: senate = \"RDD\"\nOutput: \"Dire\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd the third senator comes from Dire and he can ban the first senator's right in round 1. \nAnd in round 2, the third senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == senate.length`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁴`\n\n- `senate[i]` is either `'R'` or `'D'`.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"In the world of Dota2, there are two parties: the Radiant and the Dire.\n\nThe Dota2 senate consists of senators coming from two parties. Now the Senate wants to decide on a change in the Dota2 game. The voting for this change is a round-based procedure. In each round, each senator can exercise **one** of the two rights:\n\n- **Ban one senator's right:** A senator can make another senator lose all his rights in this and all the following rounds.\n\n- **Announce the victory:** If this senator found the senators who still have rights to vote are all from the same party, he can announce the victory and decide on the change in the game.\n\nGiven a string `senate` representing each senator's party belonging. The character `'R'` and `'D'` represent the Radiant party and the Dire party. Then if there are `n` senators, the size of the given string will be `n`.\n\nThe round-based procedure starts from the first senator to the last senator in the given order. This procedure will last until the end of voting. All the senators who have lost their rights will be skipped during the procedure.\n\nSuppose every senator is smart enough and will play the best strategy for his own party. Predict which party will finally announce the victory and change the Dota2 game. The output should be `\"Radiant\"` or `\"Dire\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: senate = \"RD\"\nOutput: \"Radiant\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd in round 2, the first senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: senate = \"RDD\"\nOutput: \"Dire\"\nExplanation: \nThe first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. \nAnd the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. \nAnd the third senator comes from Dire and he can ban the first senator's right in round 1. \nAnd in round 2, the third senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == senate.length`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁴`\n\n- `senate[i]` is either `'R'` or `'D'`.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/dota2-senate/","problemName":"Dota2 Senate","problemNumber":649,"problemSlug":"dota2-senate","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":649,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Math","Dynamic Programming"],"constraintBl